ce:section.ce:para:
The carbon nanoparticles acquired from Chlorella vulgaris underwent characterization using various spectroscopic techniques. The synthesis of CQDs derived from Chlorella vulgaris algal biomass was validated using UV–vis absorption spectroscopy (Shimadzu UV-2700 spectrophotometer, Japan) by following the procedure described by (N. Chen, Liu, et al., 2024). A 1000 μl aliquot of the CQDs derived from Chlorella vulgaris underwent dilution with 2.0 ml of Milli-Q water to ensure homogeneous dispersion. The resulting solution was then transferred into 4 ml quartz cuvettes, with one cuvette containing Milli-Q water as the reference. The analysis was conducted at a controlled temperature of 27 °C, employing spectrophotometric scanning across the wavelength range from 800 nm to 200 nm. Data was recorded using dedicated UV-probe software. Particle size and zeta potential of the CQDs were determined using dynamic light scattering (DLS) with a Mastersizer 3000 (Malvern Panalytical Malvern, United Kingdom) following the method described by Vadivel et al. (2016). For this experiment, a 1000 μl aliquot of the CQD solution underwent homogenization with Milli-Q water employing ultrasonication with a Branson Sonifier SFX probe (manufactured in USA) for 20 min. Subsequently, the prepared sample was analyzed within a 4 ml quartz cuvette, and data analysis was conducted using Mastersizer Software version 7. x. The method outlined by Zhou et al., (2021) was employed to utilize Fourier Transform Infrared (FT-IR) spectroscopy for the identification of functional groups on the synthesized CQD. The FT-IR analysis was performed at 27 °C using a Nicolet iS50 spectrophotometer, working within the mid-infrared spectrum (4000–400 cm−1). A 15 μl aliquot of the CQD solution was mixed with 200 mg of KBr and then placed onto a diamond crystal ATR cell. Subsequently, the transmittance and wavenumber spectrum were scanned and recorded. The investigation into the morphological structure of the Chlorella vulgaris-CQDs was employed by a JEOL JEM-2100Plus high-resolution transmission electron microscope (HR-TEM). The experimental approach adhered to the methodology detailed by Thangaraj et al. (2021). A 15 μl sample of the CQD solution was placed on a copper grid and subjected to a sputtering process at 30 mA for 2 min to enhance conductivity before imaging at various magnifications using Velox software. Thermal properties of the Chlorella vulgaris-CQDs were determined using Differential Scanning Calorimetry (DSC), performed with a TA Instruments Q20 under a nitrogen atmosphere as the procedure followed by Damergi et al. (2021). Temperature scans were conducted within the range of 25–350 °C, with a gradual increase of 10 °C per minute, aimed at reducing oxidation effects and precisely capturing thermal transitions. The fluorescence properties of the CQDs were evaluated by employing a fluorescence spectrophotometer (PerkinElmer Spectrum FL, Germany) by the procedure described by Xu et al. (2017). The CQDs were excited at 280 nm, with emission and excitation slit widths set at 5 and 2 nm, respectively. Photoluminescence spectra were recorded, analyzing the emission characteristics to understand the optical properties of the CQDs. The quantum yield of the newly synthesized Chlorella vulgaris-CQDs was quantified using quinine sulfate (with a known quantum yield of 54%) as a reference as the method mentioned by Anpalagan et al. (2024). Measurements were taken for both quinine sulfate solutions in 0.1 M H2SO4 and Chlorella vulgaris-CQDs, with absorbance maintained below 0.1. Both substances were excited at 360 nm to measure absorbance and integrated intensity. The quantum yield of the Chlorella vulgaris-CQDs was then calculated by using the equation:
(1)
Φ =
{
Φ r × I / I r × A r / A × η / η r
}
